            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>COPY<lb/></p>
            <p>546 N. 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr. B. Felsenthal.<lb/>
                Dear Sir&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr. Isaiah Luzzato sent me five copies of<lb/> the Pentateuch commented critically&#44; and translated in pure<lb/> Italian by his learned father &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  Four had been bespoken<lb/> by my colleagues in this city&#44; and one I have reserved for<lb/> yourself.  Will you have the kindness to inform me what means<lb/> you deem best to forward it&#63;  By mail&#44; it will&#44; of course&#44;<lb/> be attended with some expense.  If you know any persons here&#44;<lb/> who&#44; being in the habit of <sic>travelling</sic> to and fro&#44; would take<lb/> charge of it&#44; and let you have it at his arrival in Chicago&#44;<lb/> name him and the place where he can be found&#44; I will deliver<lb/> it in his hands.  The price of the work is five francs in<lb/> gold a volume&#44; which&#44; together with the large number of post&#45;<lb/>age stamps accompanying each volume&#44; will make it amount to<lb/> six dollars.<lb/></p>
            <p>You will oblige by apologizing for me to<lb/> Dr. Bunreuther for not forwarding a copy&#44; as yet&#44; to his ad&#45;<lb/>dress.  Probably&#44; I shall receive more.  If I knew positively<lb/> that I could dispose of many&#44; I would ask for them without<lb/> hesitation&#44; for to serve the family of an illustrious Jew&#44;<lb/> and the cause of Hebrew literature&#44; I cheerfully would under&#45;<lb/>take what might <sic>ential</sic> some labor&#44; but I would feel pained to<lb/> cause my Italian correspondent disappointment&#44; while I could<lb/> not&#44; in justice to my numerous family&#44; risk to be a loser.<lb/>  I send another catalogue&#44; and from that you will perceive that<lb/> they have it in contemplation to publish some of Luzzato&#39;s<lb/> works simply with a comment&#44; omitting the Italian version&#44;<lb/> which can be of little use outside of Italy.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours very truly&#44;<lb/>
                S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>Phila.&#44; 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> of January&#44; 1877.<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
